But since p is the sum from s=1 to infinity of 1/s², which is 1 + 1/2² + 1/3² + ..., so the sum from s=2 is p - 1.

Similarly, q is the sum from s=1 to infinity of 1/s³, so the sum from s=2 is q - 1.

Therefore, substituting:

\[ (p - 1) - (q - 1) = p - 1 - q + 1 = p - q \]

Yes, that seems correct. So, the double sum simplifies to p - q.

